article.description: Renee Montgomery shook off a shooting slump with seven three-pointers and 25 points to lead the No. 1 UConn Huskies to an 83-71 over Florida State.
article.headline: UConn wins Caribbean Classic finale behind Montgomery's seven 3-pointers
article.linkText: Montgomery shakes off slump as UConn wins
article.story: CANCUN, Mexico -- Top-ranked Connecticut always seems to pack a punch. Senior guard Renee Montgomery embodies that mentality. "She's one of those elite middleweights," Huskies coach Geno Auriemma said Sunday. "You have to keep the door to their dressing room closed until its time [to fight] because they can't wait to get out there. Today she had that look about her. Today she had that feel about her." Montgomery shook off a shooting slump with seven 3-pointers and 25 points, leading the top-ranked Huskies to an 83-71 victory over Florida State in the finale of the Caribbean Classic at the Moon Palace Resort. Montgomery, who played all 40 minutes, was 4-of-19 from 3-point range in her last three games. But she finished 7-of-11 Sunday, falling one short of the program's single-game record. "We knew this game was going to be a challenge, but it was also the last game we were going to play here. And in my head, I'm thinking about going home for five days [for Christmas break] and you don't want to go home off a bad game," she said. "All you do is sit around and think about it. At all cost, I wanted to have a good game." Sophomore Maya Moore added 18 points and junior center Kaili McLaren had 10 points and a career-high seven assists for the Huskies (10-0), who assisted on 31 of their 35 baskets. Tanae Davis-Cain led the Seminoles (9-4) with 25 points, including five 3-pointers. Guard Courtney Ward added 14 and Alysha Harvin had 11. The victory virtually assures the Huskies (10-0) will retain their top national ranking for 113 overall weeks, tying Tennessee for the most in history. "Whenever I'm reminded of things like that, and it's likely a character flaw of mine, is that I always think, along with what is, about what could have been," Auriemma said. "All I can think about is all those times we were No. 1 in the polls and had the best team in the country and didn't come away with the national championship." It also wrapped up the Huskies' 12th consecutive in-season tournament title, dating to a loss to Vanderbilt in Hilton Head, S.C., in 1992. UConn's winning streak at these events is 37. Connecticut had won its first two tournament games against Washington and Northern Colorado by a combined 103 points, increasing their average margin of victory this season to 39.6. But the Seminoles (9-4), against whom UConn begins a home-and-home series next season in Tallahassee, Fla., proved more capable of keeping up with the pace. One of Auriemma's teaching points in practice Saturday was executing the press. And UConn forced the Seminoles to commit seven turnovers in the first 4:40 to help open a 13-0 lead. The Seminoles did not score until Mara Freshour's 3-pointer with 15:05 remaining in the half. But Florida State eventually found its balance and outscored UConn over the last 35 minutes (71-70). Four 3-pointers by Montgomery and McLaren's strong game in relief of Tina Charles, who had four fouls in 18 minutes, kept UConn comfortably ahead at 43-29. "Geno does such a fabulous job," Florida State coach Sue Semrau said. "His players are so disciplined. ... They play great together and they play hard. They are the best team in America."
